## 6. Product Principles

> **Prompts**
> *   What are the **tie-breaker rules** when two reasonable
>     requirements conflict? These are the principles a reviewer
>     should be able to cite to reject a proposed feature.
> *   Aim for 5–8 principles. Each principle should be falsifiable
>     ("we never do X"), not aspirational ("we strive for X").
> *   Cover at least: a *performance/architecture* principle, a
>     *configuration* principle, an *output/interface* principle, a
>     *dependency* principle, an *error-handling* principle, and a
>     *verification* principle.

These principles are the tie-breakers when requirements conflict.

1.  **<Principle 1 — short title>.** <One-paragraph rule, including
    what it rules out.>
2.  **<Principle 2>.** <…>
3.  **<Principle 3>.** <…>
4.  **<Principle 4>.** <…>
5.  **<Principle 5>.** <…>
6.  **<Principle 6>.** <…>
7.  **Verifiable.** Every behaviour worth describing is captured as
    an HLR/LLR with at least one bound test. The
    [Traceability Matrix](Traceability.md) is the contract.

